Introduction & Motivation

It is common to see college students who complain about the quality of foods provided by school-owned dining services, which leads people to wonder whether students will turn away from school dining options to eating at restaurants outside. Apparently, there are more variables that could have an impact on students eating habits. These variables include the year in college, employment status, grades, and identity. The reasons why these variables matter will be examined in the later parts of this project. The study that will be conducted could potentially lead to useful insights for restaurant business owners. In detail, those who have plans to enter the restaurant business could better find an optimal location for their restaurant businesses. The rent or price of commercial property near the school is usually more expensive. The restaurant owner could use the data in this research to determine whether its worth it to rent or buy the commercial property for opening up a restaurant with the premium.

Problem Addressed & Hypothesis¶

Primary Question:¶

How often do you eat off campus per week? (Q25)

Variable Questions:¶

  • What year are you at Emory? (Q1)
  • Do you currently have a job? (Q66)
  • What is your cumulative GPA up to this point? (Q8)
  • What ethnicity do you identify as? (Q5)

Hypothesis:¶

  • Senior students will have a greater mean of eating outside than other groups of students
  • Students who have a job will have a greater means of eating outside than students who dont have a job
  • Students with a lower GPA will have a higher mean of eating outside
  • Students who identify as Asian will have a greater mean of eating outside than other groups of students

The purpose of this project is to analyze the possible factors that contribute to Econ 220 students’ frequency of eating outside.¶

Literature Support¶

We expect that higher-year students tend to eat more often off-campus compared to lower-grade students. In other words, higher-year students (junior and senior) and students that have a job are more likely to eat off-campus, which means that the juniors and seniors mean of the frequency of eating off campus would be significantly greater than the number for the freshmen and sophomores.

According to the research published by Jean Adams in 2015, 27.1% of adults and 19.0% of children at least eat out more than once a week.(Adams) Although the researchers didnt determine whether there is a positive relationship between age and frequency of eating outside, its reasonable to suspect there is such a relationship.

According to this graph, we can tell that there is a positive relationship between income and the proportion of food spending on food away from home, which means that people probably tend to eat out more often as their income increases. Inspired by this observation, we realized that higher grade students in college are more likely to find paid internships/part-time jobs than the lower grade students do. Therefore, it is likely that the higher grade students would eat out more often than the lower grade students.

In 2014, Marte from the Washington Post conducted a study to research the relationship between grades and incomes. In the research, Marte discovered that for a one-point increase in a person's high school GPA, average annual earnings in adulthood increased by about 12 percent for men and about 14 percent for women. We suspect that there is a positive relationship between income and frequency of eating out, but we have not proven the correlation between them. It is possible that those who have higher grades, who happen to have higher incomes, tend to eat out more often. Therefore, we decide to verify whether there is a relationship between grades and eating out.

According to Jim from CDC, Multivariate adjusted minutes per day spent on primary eating and drinking were 66.4 for noncitizens, 66.5 for naturalized citizens, and 60.1 for US-born individuals. (Jim) Due to this result, we would assume that the difference between eating time is due to eating at home and eating out. Therefore, it is reasonable to assume that there is a relationship between the frequency of eating out and ethnicities.

#Find missing data in each variables and remove unwanted missing data
data['year'].isna().sum()
data['Ethnicity'].isna().sum()
data['GPA'].isna().sum()
data['q25'].isna().sum()
data['q66'].isna().sum()
data = data.dropna()

#Cleaning variable year
#Use .replace to replace different ways of describing grade level as numerical number from 1 to 4
#Change variable type to 'category'
data['year'] = data['year'].str.strip()
data['year'] = data['year'].replace("2024", "2", regex=True).replace("2023", "2", regex=True).replace("3rd year", "3", regex=True).replace("2nd", "2", regex=True).replace("2 year", "2", regex=True).replace("Sophmore", "2", regex=True).replace("Sophomore", "2", regex=True).replace("3rd", "3", regex=True).replace("Senior", "4", regex=True).astype('category')
data['year'].value_counts(dropna=False)

#Cleaning variable Ethnicity
data['Ethnicity'] = data['Ethnicity'].replace("No answer text provided.", "More than one race.", regex=True).astype('category')
#data['Ethnicity'].value_counts(dropna=False)

#Cleaning variable GPA
data['GPA'] = data['GPA'].str.strip()
data['GPA'] = data['GPA'].replace("3,1", "3.1", regex=True).replace("3.76\n\nDon't have a high school GPA", "3.76", regex=True).replace("3,85", "3.85", regex=True).replace("3,94", "3.94", regex=True).replace("3.3, 3.98", "3.3", regex=True).replace("Sophmore", "2", regex=True).astype('float')
#data['GPA'].value_counts(dropna=False)


#Cleaning variable q25
data['q25'] = data['q25'].replace("0.25", "0", regex=True).replace("2-3 times", "3", regex=True).astype('float')
#data['q25'].value_counts(dropna=False)

#Cleaning variable q66
data['q66'] = data['q66'].astype('category')
#data['q66'].value_counts(dropna=False)

Dataset Analysis

Prior to any data analysis, it is important to understand our sample population. In our research, three sets of categorical variables and two sets of numerical variables are involved. The two sets of categorical variables are students grade level, whether they have a job, and students ethnicity. The numerical variable is the frequency of eating out and students GPA score.

Analysis Confidence Intervals and Testing¶

In this project, the analysis on confidence intervals and testing are using a=0.05 as the level of signifance.

ANOVA Test¶

Problem addressed: What year are you at Emory vs. How often do you eat off campus per week

  • Null Hypothesis: there is no difference in means among the five groups of the students grade
  • Alternative Hypothesis: The means for the four groups of students grades are different
In [19]:
year_1 = data1[data1['Year']=='1']
year_2 = data1[data1['Year']=='2']
year_3 = data1[data1['Year']=='3']
year_4 = data1[data1['Year']=='4']
year_5 = data1[data1['Year']=='5']

# stats f_oneway functions takes the groups as input and returns ANOVA F and p value
fvalue, pvalue = stats.f_oneway(year_1['Frequency'], year_2['Frequency'], year_3['Frequency'],year_4['Frequency'],year_5['Frequency'])


print("\nANOVA Test for differences in frequency by grade of students:\n P-Value:{0}\n F-Statistic:{1}\n". 
        format(round(pvalue,3),
               round(fvalue,3))) 

ANOVA Test for differences in frequency by grade of students:
 P-Value:0.041
 F-Statistic:2.599
  • In this case, because there is a total of 100 sample point(n=100) and there are five groups of students' grade level, the degree of freedom 1 equal 4(DF1 = NbGroup 1) and the degree of freedom 2 equal 95(DF2 = N NbGroup). Thus, based on significant level of 0.05(a=0.05), the critical value in this case equal 2.4675. Since F-value of 2.599 is greater than the critial value of 2.4675, and p-value is less than 0.05, We have statistically significant evidence to show that there is a difference in students'grade level of frequency of eating out.

Two Sample T Test¶

Problem addressed: Do you currently have a job(YES or NO) vs. How often do you eat off campus per week

  • Null Hypothesis: the mean of eating off campus per week for students with a job and without a job is equal
  • Alternative Hypothesis: the mean of eating off campus per week for students with a job and without a job is not equal
In [414]:
job_y = data1[data1['Job']=='Yes']
job_n = data1[data1['Job']=='No']

print('\nDifference in means between with a job vs without a job\n',
      round(data1.groupby('Job')['Frequency'].mean()[0]-
            data1.groupby('Job')['Frequency'].mean()[1],5))

#run independent sample T-Test 
tStat, pValue = stats.ttest_ind(job_y['Frequency'], 
                                job_n['Frequency'])

print("\nT-test for differences in Frequency by whether having a job:\n P-Value:{0}\n T-Statistic:{1}\n". 
        format(round(pValue,3),
               round(tStat,3)))

Conclusion & Summary¶

What year are you at Emory vs. How often do you eat off campus per week¶

  • Although there is not enought evidence to suggest that there is a difference in means of frequency of eating among the five groups of students grade, a few possible explanation can be made based on the result. As mentioned in the previosu section, the average frequency of eating out is higher for the students in fifth grade in college, but there are only two students in fifth grade in the sample. Since the sample size in the fifth grade student is relative small, it might not be a great representative sample reflecting the population mean. Therefore, it is more reasonable to interpret it as the first year students eat out most frequently among the five group. A possible explainaiton might be that the first year stduent is more likely to have less school work than higher grade of students and thus more liekly to spend their free time eating outside.

Do you currently have a job(YES or NO) vs. How often do you eat off campus per week¶

  • Our result does not shows a significant relationship of frequency of eating outside between student having and not having a job. Although it is more resonable to assume that student who have a job is more likely to eat outside because of having income resource, it is also possible that a student with a job is more likely to distribute their wealth based on individual financial planning and thus cooking by oneself other than eating outside.

What year are you at Emory vs. How often do you eat off campus per week¶

  • Our result indicates that there is not enough evidence to suggest that there is a relationship between students GPA scores and students frequency of eating outside. In other words, whether a student like to eat outside or at school does not play role in determinaing individual's GPA scores.

What ethnicity do you identify as vs. How often do you eat off campus per week¶

  • Lastly, We do not have statistically significant evidence to show that there is a difference in students'grade level of frequency of eating out. However, from the visual examination session, since Asian has the second higher eating out frequency mean, it is possible to assuem that Asian is more liekly to eating out becasue of international student is a great portion within this group. Since international student usually have different backgrounds and habits based on each indvidual's nationality, they are more likely to prefer their own country's food instead of eating at shcool's dinnig hall.
